<DOC><DOCNO> AP880826-0265 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0738EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-26 0329</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0344</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Rises</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar held steady against major currencies incalm European trading today as the market reassessed trendsfollowing a round of interest rate hikes. Gold prices rose.   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was weaker in earlytrading in Frankfurt but was recovering later in European marketsafter short-covering and profit-taking on long non-dollar positions.   On Thursday the U.S. currency fell after the West German centralbank raised its discount rate by half a point to 3.5 percent.France, Switzerland, the Netherlands and Austria also hiked theirkey rates.   It was also pushed lower after Deutsche Bundesbank PresidentKarl Otto Poehl said the West German central bank ``will continueto do everything to stem the decline of the Deutsche mark againstthe dollar.''   One trader said Friday that the market was taking a breatherfollowing the activity caused by interest rate increases.   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,the dollar fell 0.26 yen to a closing 133.50 yen. Later, in London,it was quoted at 133.75 yen.   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday'srates, included: 1.8630 West German marks, unchanged from Thursday;1.5730 Swiss francs, up from 1.5715; 6.3332 French francs, up from6.3275; 2.1042 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1030; 1,385.75 Italianlire, up from 1,384.13; and 1.2365 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2342.   In London, the British pound was trading at $1.6950, cheaper forbuyers than Thursday's late $1.6995.   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $433.40 a troy ounce. Atmidmorning, the City's five major bullion dealers fixed arecommended price of $433.75, up from Thursday's late bid of$433.50.   In Zurich, the bid price was $433.80, up from $433.50 bid lateThursday.   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped 86 cents to close at a bid$435.24.   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.72 a troyounce, down from $6.77 at Thursday's close.</TEXT></DOC>